1.5.0
  Build parity with traditional bundlers (slicejs-cli 4.0.x):
  - Relative `.json` imports work: default import = whole document, named
    imports = top-level keys (like Vite/webpack).
  - `slice build --sourcemap` emits a `.map` next to each minified bundle
    (maps to the readable pre-minified bundle; off by default so source isn't
    shipped unless asked).
  - `slice build --hash-filenames` inserts a content hash into bundle filenames
    (`slice-bundle.home.a1b2c3d4.js`) for immutable CDN caching; the runtime
    loads every bundle by the config's filename, so hashing just works. Off by
    default (stable names).
  - Note (already true, reinforced): env vars are runtime, not build-time —
    `SLICE_PUBLIC_*` from `.env`/`process.env`, served by the server and read via
    `slice.env.*`. There is no `import.meta.env` build-time injection (and none is
    needed): change config without rebuilding, secrets stay server-side.
  Files touched: references/config-theming-cli.md.

1.4.0
  Build hardening (slicejs-cli 4.0.x):
  - npm deps: a minimal runtime process/global shim now covers dynamic
    references (process.platform, process.env[key], free global) that the
    build-time defines can't fold — still no Node polyfill (no Buffer/stream/fs).
    Text assets (.glsl/.vert/.frag/.txt) load as strings. Dev disk cache
    (node_modules/.slice-deps) is pruned per package on version upgrade.
  - Relative helper modules a component imports may now import AND re-export:
    `export * from './x'` and `export { y } from './x'` / `export { z } from 'pkg'`
    are inlined and wired (absolute/URL re-exports unsupported).
  - `slice.build(<name>)` is resolved statically for a literal, an
    expression-free template, or an identifier/config-member that resolves to
    one (imported const, `viewMap[key]` with a literal map) — those get bundled.
    A truly dynamic name warns (`⚠️ Dynamic slice.build(...)`) and loads
    individually at runtime instead of failing silently.
  - Reproducible builds: `SOURCE_DATE_EPOCH` (integer epoch seconds) fixes the
    timestamps embedded in bundle metadata/config, so a clean rebuild is
    byte-identical.
